Wash and dry produce.

Dice @tomato{1}. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @onion{1}; mince a few slices until you have 2 tbsp (4 tbsp for 4 servings). Zest and quarter @lime{1}. Halve, core, and thinly slice @long green pepper{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @tomato{1}(diced), @onion{1}(minced), a squeeze of lime juice, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

In a separate small bowl, combine @sour cream{3%tbsp} with a squeeze of lime juice. Season with salt and pepper. Stir in @water{} 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @long green pepper{1}(halved, cored, sliced); cook until lightly browned and slightly softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add @onion{1}(sliced); cook, stirring occasionally, until veggies are browned and tender, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir in half the @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tbsp} (you'll use the rest in the next step) and a splash of water. Cook, stirring, until veggies are coated and water has mostly evaporated. Season with salt and pepper.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

Open package of @shrimp{10%oz} and drain off any excess liquid.

Rinse shrimp under cold water; pat dry with #paper towels{}. Swap in shrimp or beef for chicken.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for veggies over medium-high heat. Add shrimp and remaining @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tbsp}; cook, stirring frequently, until shrimp is browned, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Stir in @Tex-Mex paste{1}, lime zest, and a squeeze of lime juice until shrimp is coated and cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes}. Taste and season with salt and pepper. Turn off heat.

Meanwhile, wrap @flour tortillas{6} in damp #paper towels{} and microwave until warm and pliable, ~{30%seconds}.

Divide tortillas between plates and fill with shrimp and veggies. Top with pico de gallo, @Monterey Jack cheese{1/4%cup}, and lime crema. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Serve shrimp, veggies, pico de gallo, Monterey Jack, lime crema, and lime wedges in separate bowls or plates for a build-your-own fajita bar!

> Shellfish is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.